<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="486" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[685,1172,460,1729]" pageId="9" pageNumber="486">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,814,805,826]" pageId="9" pageNumber="486">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[828,1067,805,827]" class="Insecta" family="Noteridae" genus="Canthysellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="486" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruanus">
<emphasis box="[828,1067,805,827]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="486">Canthysellus peruanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by the following combination of characters: (a) metatibia as in 
<figureCitation box="[923,983,858,879]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[175,215,532,551]" captionTargetBox="[154,631,194,508]" captionTargetId="figure-424@5.[151,638,193,509]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 6–7. Canthysellus species,hind legs.6) C.buqueti, male, a = setae of inner margin of metatibia, b = posterior metatibial spur, serration is diagnostic of the genus; 7) C. peruanus, paratype, male, a = setae of inner margin of metatibia. Scale bars = 0.25 mm" pageId="9" pageNumber="486">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
, with inner margin densely setose, setae slender, hair-like, metatarsomere I similarly setose; (b) line of setae on prosternum as in 
<figureCitation box="[845,912,938,959]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[197,237,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[179,1186,1165,1639]" captionTargetId="figure-315@4.[173,1193,1165,1639]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 4–5. Canthysellus species, pro- and metasterna and metacoxae (noterid platform) with studies of prosternal setae. 4) C. buqueti, male, a and b = variation of prosternal setae; 5) C. peruanus, paratype, male, a = enlarged view of prosternal setae. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." pageId="9" pageNumber="486">Fig. 5a</figureCitation>
, not extending laterally past lateral margins of narrowest portion of prosternal process; (c) aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[944,1045,991,1013]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[175,215,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[163,1171,1241,1638]" captionTargetId="figure-477@5.[151,1171,1241,1639]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 8–10. Canthysellus species, aedeagi. 8) C. buqueti, Suriname; 9) C. sipaliwini, holotype, Suriname; 10) C. peruanus, paratype, Peru. a = median lobe, left lateral aspect, b = median lobe, dorsal aspect, c = median lobe, right lateral aspect, d = left lateral lobe, e = right lateral lobe. Scale bars = 0.25 mm." pageId="9" pageNumber="486">Fig. 10a–e</figureCitation>
, median lobe only weakly expanded ventrally, distally parallelsided and weakly attenuate to subtruncate apex in lateral aspect (
<figureCitation box="[832,944,1071,1092]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[175,215,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[163,1171,1241,1638]" captionTargetId="figure-477@5.[151,1171,1241,1639]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 8–10. Canthysellus species, aedeagi. 8) C. buqueti, Suriname; 9) C. sipaliwini, holotype, Suriname; 10) C. peruanus, paratype, Peru. a = median lobe, left lateral aspect, b = median lobe, dorsal aspect, c = median lobe, right lateral aspect, d = left lateral lobe, e = right lateral lobe. Scale bars = 0.25 mm." pageId="9" pageNumber="486">Fig. 10a, c</figureCitation>
), left lateral lobe with dense tuft of setae produced from weakly lobed apex (
<figureCitation box="[744,827,1124,1145]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[175,215,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[163,1171,1241,1638]" captionTargetId="figure-477@5.[151,1171,1241,1639]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 8–10. Canthysellus species, aedeagi. 8) C. buqueti, Suriname; 9) C. sipaliwini, holotype, Suriname; 10) C. peruanus, paratype, Peru. a = median lobe, left lateral aspect, b = median lobe, dorsal aspect, c = median lobe, right lateral aspect, d = left lateral lobe, e = right lateral lobe. Scale bars = 0.25 mm." pageId="9" pageNumber="486">Fig. 10d</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="487" pageId="9" pageNumber="486" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[685,1172,460,1729]" lastBlockId="10.[173,660,194,1596]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="487" pageId="9" pageNumber="486">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,829,1151,1172]" pageId="9" pageNumber="486">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[841,929,1151,1172]" pageId="9" pageNumber="486">Holotype</typeStatus>
.Male. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="486">Color and appearance:</emphasis>
Shiny, elytra superficially iridescent; maculate, weakly bicolorous with elytra only slightly darker than head and pronotum. Color of head, pronotum, and maculae reddish brown; color of elytra very dark reddish brown; maculae as in 
<figureCitation box="[685,744,1310,1331]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[197,237,543,562]" captionTargetBox="[181,1189,208,518]" captionTargetId="figure-279@4.[173,1193,183,526]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 1–3. Canthysellus species, dorsal and lateral habitus. 1) C. buqueti, male; 2) C. sipaliwini, holotype, male;" pageId="9" pageNumber="486">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
, each elytron with 1 spot distally near apex and with an irregular band near elytral midlength extending from lateral margin to suture, often broken into a series of 2 or 3 spots with margins blurred and meeting. Color of venter dark reddish brown, with color of noterid platform and sutures only slightly darker than rest of ventral surface; color of legs slightly lighter than venter, margins dark. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[745,807,1522,1543]" pageId="9" pageNumber="486">Head:</emphasis>
Dorsal surface with microsculpture consisting of small, round, isodiametric cells. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[685,777,1575,1596]" pageId="9" pageNumber="486">Thorax:</emphasis>
Pronotum with lateral bead broad, 1.13X width of antennomere VII. Prosternum medially with close, transverse line or tuft of 5 stiff setae, line of setae continuous medially, not extending past lateral margins of prosternal process. Prosternal process and noterid platform setose, setae very short, stout, produced from punctures, distinctly spaced and evenly distributed (
<figureCitation box="[180,239,247,268]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[197,237,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[179,1186,1165,1639]" captionTargetId="figure-315@4.[173,1193,1165,1639]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 4–5. Canthysellus species, pro- and metasterna and metacoxae (noterid platform) with studies of prosternal setae. 4) C. buqueti, male, a and b = variation of prosternal setae; 5) C. peruanus, paratype, male, a = enlarged view of prosternal setae. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." pageId="10" pageNumber="487">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Metatibia densely setose on inner margin (
<figureCitation box="[180,252,274,295]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[175,215,532,551]" captionTargetBox="[154,631,194,508]" captionTargetId="figure-424@5.[151,638,193,509]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 6–7. Canthysellus species,hind legs.6) C.buqueti, male, a = setae of inner margin of metatibia, b = posterior metatibial spur, serration is diagnostic of the genus; 7) C. peruanus, paratype, male, a = setae of inner margin of metatibia. Scale bars = 0.25 mm" pageId="10" pageNumber="487">Fig. 7a</figureCitation>
); setae slender, hair-like, expanding from single line at base to dense field distally; field restricted to inner margin. Metatarsomere I with inner margin similarly setose to metatibia. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="487">Abdomen:</emphasis>
Aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[406,518,379,401]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[175,215,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[163,1171,1241,1638]" captionTargetId="figure-477@5.[151,1171,1241,1639]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 8–10. Canthysellus species, aedeagi. 8) C. buqueti, Suriname; 9) C. sipaliwini, holotype, Suriname; 10) C. peruanus, paratype, Peru. a = median lobe, left lateral aspect, b = median lobe, dorsal aspect, c = median lobe, right lateral aspect, d = left lateral lobe, e = right lateral lobe. Scale bars = 0.25 mm." pageId="10" pageNumber="487">Fig. 10a–e</figureCitation>
; median lobe curved dorsally, divided ventrally by deep groove, groove ceasing and sides meeting at about midlength of lobe, left side expanded ventrally at midlength, distal third of lobe subparallel and distally attenuate to truncate apex in lateral aspect, distal portion distinctly curved in dorsal aspect; left lateral lobe broad, weakly curved toward median lobe, with dense setal tuft produced apically from inner surface of weakly lobed apex (
<figureCitation box="[516,598,619,640]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[175,215,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[163,1171,1241,1638]" captionTargetId="figure-477@5.[151,1171,1241,1639]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 8–10. Canthysellus species, aedeagi. 8) C. buqueti, Suriname; 9) C. sipaliwini, holotype, Suriname; 10) C. peruanus, paratype, Peru. a = median lobe, left lateral aspect, b = median lobe, dorsal aspect, c = median lobe, right lateral aspect, d = left lateral lobe, e = right lateral lobe. Scale bars = 0.25 mm." pageId="10" pageNumber="487">Fig. 10d</figureCitation>
); right lateral lobe broad, ventral margin broadly rounded (
<figureCitation box="[179,258,672,693]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[175,215,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[163,1171,1241,1638]" captionTargetId="figure-477@5.[151,1171,1241,1639]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 8–10. Canthysellus species, aedeagi. 8) C. buqueti, Suriname; 9) C. sipaliwini, holotype, Suriname; 10) C. peruanus, paratype, Peru. a = median lobe, left lateral aspect, b = median lobe, dorsal aspect, c = median lobe, right lateral aspect, d = left lateral lobe, e = right lateral lobe. Scale bars = 0.25 mm." pageId="10" pageNumber="487">Fig. 10e</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[275,425,672,693]" pageId="10" pageNumber="487">Measurements:</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[431,520,672,693]" pageId="10" pageNumber="487">Holotype</typeStatus>
: L = 
